Proudly guarding the New York Public library on Fifth Avenue are two marble lions “Patience” and “Fortitude”. These lions have witnessed countless parades and been adorned with holly wreaths during the winter holidays and floral wreaths in springtime.  They have been photographed alongside countless tourists, replicated as bookends, caricatured in cartoons and illustrated in numerous children’s books.  Their names were given to them by Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia in the 1930’s in honor of qualities New Yorkers possessed and would need to survive the economic depression.

An oasis in the middle of Brooklyn, Warren Place Mews consists of 34 Gothic cottages built in the late 1800’s for the working class of Brooklyn, they all share an English courtyard and are closed off to the rest of Cobble Hill by a gate.  One of the most charming blocks of Cobble Hill, if not all of Brooklyn.
